# Documentation Standards

## README Philosophy

**READMEs should be light and high-level.** Code changes frequently; READMEs shouldn't need constant updates.

### README Structure

```markdown
# Project Name

One sentence describing what this does and why it exists.

## What It Does

2-3 paragraphs max describing:
- The problem it solves
- Who uses it (internal tool, customer-facing, etc.)
- Key features at a glance

## Quick Start

```bash
docker-compose up --build
```

## Architecture

Link to architecture docs (if they exist elsewhere).

## Related Projects

- Links to other repos in the ecosystem
- How this fits into the bigger picture
```

### What NOT to Include

- ❌ Detailed API documentation (use OpenAPI/Swagger)
- ❌ Internal implementation details
- ❌ Function-level documentation
- ❌ Changelogs (use git history + PRs)

### What TO Include

- ✅ Project purpose (the "why")
- ✅ How to run it locally
- ✅ High-level architecture diagram (if complex)
- ✅ Contact/context for questions

## Technical Documentation

Technical docs live elsewhere (Notion, Confluence, or a dedicated docs repo). READMEs point to them but don't duplicate.

## Code Comments

- Explain the "why", not the "what"
- Document non-obvious business logic
- Call out cheat prevention measures
- Flag security-critical sections

```go
// ValidateTEEAttestation ensures the response came from an
// enclave with the expected measurement. This prevents 
// miners from running outside secure hardware.
func ValidateTEEAttestation(attestation []byte) error {
    // ... implementation
}
```
